<title>USA: EC opposes Boeing single-supplier deals - WSJ.</title>
<headline>EC opposes Boeing single-supplier deals - WSJ.</headline>
<dateline>NEW YORK 1997-05-23</dateline>
<text>
<p>The European Commission was seeking to have Boeing Co. abandon its single-supplier deals with U.S. airlines and make other concessions to secure antitrust approval for its planned acquisition of McDonnell Douglas Corp., the Wall Street Journal said on Friday.</p>
<p>In its electronic edition, the Journal quoted a senior European Union official as saying the prime concern was Boeing's long-term sales agreements with AMR Corp.'s American Airlines and Delta Air Lines Inc.</p>
<p>&quot;Such exclusive deals fly in the face of free competition,&quot; an unnamed EU official told the Journal. &quot;You cannot close your eyes and forget about the consequences.&quot;</p>
<p>The EU official said there were other issues at play as well, and that pulling out of those deals may not be enough to satisfy the commission's concerns.</p>
<p>The commission Wednesday formally filed a statement of objections to the proposed $14 billion merger.</p>
